<doc id="1256331" wikidata="Q777327" url="?curid=1256331" title="Euclea">
<text>Euclea, from the Greek &quot;eukleia&quot; meaning &quot;glory and fame&quot;, denotes a group of flowering plants in the Ebenaceae or ebony family. They were described as a genus by Linnaeus in 1774. The genus includes evergreen trees and shrubs, native to Africa, the Comoro Islands and Arabia. Several species are used for timber, producing a hard, dark heartwood timber similar to ebony.

==Species==
There are some 16 to 18 species, including:

*&quot;Euclea acutifolia&quot; – Cape Province
*&quot;Euclea angolensis&quot; – Angola
*&quot;Euclea asperrima&quot; – Namibia
*&quot;Euclea balfourii&quot; 
*&quot;Euclea coriacea&quot; – Lesotho, South Africa
*&quot;Euclea crispa&quot; – southern Africa
*&quot;Euclea dewinteri&quot; – Limpopo
*&quot;Euclea divinorum&quot; – from Ethiopia to KwaZulu-Natal
*&quot;Euclea lancea&quot; – Cape Province
*&quot;Euclea laurina&quot; 
*&quot;Euclea natalensis&quot; – from Somalia to KwaZulu-Natal
*&quot;Euclea neghellensis&quot; – Ethiopia
*&quot;Euclea polyandra&quot; – Cape Province
*&quot;Euclea pseudebenus&quot; – Angola, Namibia, Cape Province
*&quot;Euclea racemosa&quot; – from Egypt to Cape Province; Comoros, Oman, Yemen
*&quot;Euclea sekhukhuniensis&quot; – Mpumalanga
*&quot;Euclea tomentosa&quot; – Cape Province
*&quot;Euclea undulata&quot; – from Zimbabwe to KwaZulu-Natal
